\section{Stability Analysis of the Conical State}
The purpose of this section is to demonstrate that the energy of the variational state given in Eq.~(2) of the main text
is a decreasing function of $\Delta_2$ for $\Delta_2 \ll 1$. In other words, we will demonstrate that the single-${\bf Q}_1$
conical state ($\Delta_2$=0) is unstable towards the development of a second ${\bf Q}_2$ component, as long as 
the magnetic field, $H$, and the easy-axis anisotropy, $A$, are non-zero.  We will then expand the 
total energy per site, $E(\Delta_2)$, to fourth order in $\Delta_2$. In general, the total energy per site of an arbitrary state is:
\begin{eqnarray}
E = \langle \mathcal{H} \rangle = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{\bf q} |\langle {\bf S}_{\bf q}  \rangle |^2
- \frac{H \langle S_{\bf 0} \rangle}{\sqrt{N}}
- \frac{A}{N} \sum_j \langle (S^z_j)^2 \rangle, 
\label{energy}
\end{eqnarray}
with
\begin{eqnarray}
{\bf S}_{\bf q} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{j} {\bf S}_j e^{i {\bf q} \cdot {\bf r}_j}.
\end{eqnarray}
For the state under consideration, we have:
\begin{eqnarray}
S^z_j = \cos{\tilde \theta} \left [ 1 - x \cos{{\bf Q}_3 \cdot {\bf r}_j} - \frac{x^2}{2} \cos^2{\! {\bf Q}_3 \cdot {\bf r}_j}
- \frac{x^3}{2} \cos^3{\! {\bf Q}_3 \cdot {\bf r}_j} - \frac{5x^4}{8} \cos^4{\! {\bf Q}_3 \cdot {\bf r}_j} + {\cal O}(\Delta^5_2) \right],
\end{eqnarray}
with

