\section{Low-Temperature Phase for weak easy-axis anisotropy}

In this section we compare the Monte Carlo finite temperature phase diagram shown in Fig.~2(a) of the main text  with 
the $T=0$ variational phase diagram of Ref.~\cite{leonov2015multiply} for weak easy-axis anisotropy. As shown in Fig.~2(a),  the single-${\bf Q}$ conical state and the single-${\bf Q}$ vertical spiral are the only ordered states at $T=0.18$ and low magnetic field values. 
Our Monte Carlo results show that these single-${\bf Q}$ states evolve into multiple-${\bf Q}$ states upon lowering the temperature, as shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig:data_supple_smallani}. This behavior is consistent with the $T=0$ variational calculations of Ref. ~\cite{leonov2015multiply}. For weak anisotropy, the low-$T$ single-${\bf Q}_1$ vertical spiral is unstable over a finite field window 
towards the development of a spin modulation in the direction perpendicular to the original spin polarization plane. As it is shown in Figs.~\ref{Fig:data_supple_smallani} (a-c), this additional spin modulation has equal intensity ${\bf Q}_2$ and ${\bf Q}_3$ components. In addition, the single-${\bf Q}$ conical spiral in the small but finite $A$ region becomes a multiple-${\bf Q}$ conical spiral at low enough temperatures [see Figs.~\ref{Fig:data_supple_smallani} (d-i)]. Our results then show that the multiple-${\bf Q}$ $T=0$ states obtained for small single-ion anisotropy become unstable at relatively small temperatures.

